            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Where Copy.ai wins:</strong> if your job is GTM automation or short-form marketing copy, Workflows and the chat interface are excellent. <strong>Where theStacc wins:</strong> if your job is growing organic traffic with published SEO articles. Different jobs.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Copy.ai?</h2>
        <p>Copy.ai is an AI writing and workflow automation platform founded in 2020 by Paul Yacoubian and Chris Lu. It launched as a short-form AI copywriter — generating ad copy, email subject lines, social captions, and product descriptions using GPT models. The company raised $13.9M Series A led by Wing VC and grew to 10M+ registered users by 2022.</p>

        <p>In 2023, Copy.ai pivoted to a "GTM AI Platform", adding three new pillars:</p>

        <ol>
          <li><strong>Workflows</strong> — multi-step AI pipelines that chain prompts, data lookups, and actions</li>
          <li><strong>Infobase</strong> — centralised brand knowledge that every Workflow can reference</li>
          <li><strong>Sales-focused features</strong> — lead enrichment, personalised outreach, CRM integrations</li>
        </ol>

        <p>The original copywriting engine still works. The new positioning targets sales and marketing teams competing with Clay, Apollo, and Outreach more than ChatGPT or Jasper.</p>

        <p>What Copy.ai is <em>not</em>: an SEO platform. It does not research keywords, analyse SERPs, optimise content against competitors, or publish anything to your website.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">ℹ️ Company background</div>
          <p>Founded in 2020 in Memphis by Paul Yacoubian and Chris Lu. Raised $13.9M Series A from Wing VC in 2021. Pivoted to GTM AI in 2023 under the bet that workflow automation, not copywriting, is the bigger market. Team is around 70 people. The free plan is a deliberate top-of-funnel lever.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="features">Copy.ai features — the full 2026 walkthrough</h2>

        <h3>1. Chat — the AI writing surface</h3>
        <p>The core writing experience is a chat interface where you describe what you need and the AI generates it. Models include GPT-4o, Claude, and Copy.ai's fine-tuned models. Output covers blog drafts (1,000–3,000 words), ad copy, email sequences, social captions, and rewrites. Quality is comparable to ChatGPT-4 for general copywriting. For SEO content specifically, the gap is significant — Copy.ai does not know your target keywords, competitor SERP structure, or topical authority gaps.</p>

        <h3>2. Workflows — the GTM differentiator</h3>
        <p>The most innovative feature in the suite. Build a multi-step AI pipeline visually: scrape a LinkedIn URL, enrich with company data, generate a personalised cold email, push to your CRM. Workflows replace ad-hoc ChatGPT prompts with repeatable automation. The feature competes directly with Clay and Apollo for GTM workflow automation, and is the strongest reason a 2026 buyer chooses Copy.ai over Jasper.</p>

        <h3>3. Infobase — brand knowledge memory</h3>
        <p>Upload brand guidelines, product details, customer profiles, and case studies. Every Chat conversation and Workflow can reference Infobase, producing on-brand output without re-prompting. Useful for teams. Less useful for solo users.</p>

        <h3>4. Templates</h3>
        <p>90+ templates across blog posts, ads, emails, social, sales sequences, and product descriptions. Solid coverage. Most users settle on 3–5 they use weekly.</p>

        <h3>5. Brand Voice training</h3>
        <p>Train a brand voice model on past content. All outputs respect the trained voice. Quality is decent — not as fine-tuned as Jasper's brand voice but functional for most teams.</p>

        <h3>6. Integrations</h3>
        <p>Native Salesforce, HubSpot, Slack, Zapier, and webhook integrations. The GTM pivot shows in the integration choices — sales tools over content tools.</p>

        <h2 id="pricing">Copy.ai pricing — what it really costs in 2026</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Plan</th><th>Monthly</th><th>Annual / mo</th><th>Words / mo</th><th>Workflows</th><th>Users</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Free</strong></td><td>$0</td><td>$0</td><td>2,000</td><td>Limited</td><td>1</td></tr>
